</i></p><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-14_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">The Teaching Regulation Agency (TRA) plays a pivotal role in maintaining high standards within the teaching profession in England. As an executive agency of the Department for Education, the TRA’s mission is to ensure that those entering the teaching profession meet rigorous standards and those already in the profession maintain them. In this blog, Dr Richard Dune delves into the role of the TRA, key facts and statistics, essential definitions, and best practices for implementing relevant legislation and regulations. </span>
</p></div></div></div></div></div><button type="button" style="visibility:visible" aria-label="Previous" class="pf-slider-prev none hide"></button><button type="button" style="visibility:visible" aria-label="Next" class="pf-slider-next none hide"></button></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-873f" data-category="Collection Suggestion" data-name="Tea" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-kYHfwS doYKjf pf-16_ pf-color-scheme-1"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-hAcGzb cVhebe"><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-17_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-18_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-19_ pf-heading-1-h3">Key facts and statistics</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-bQtKYq czWvgn pf-21_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-22_ pf-text-1"><strong>Establishment </strong>- The TRA was established on 1 April 2018, succeeding the National College for Teaching and Leadership.




</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-24_ pf-text-1"><strong>Teacher workforce </strong>- As of 2023, there are approximately 500,000 teachers in England, according to the Department for Education.


</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-26_ pf-text-1"><strong>Qualified Teacher Status (QTS) </strong>- Annually, the TRA awards Qualified Teacher Status (QTS) to over 30,000 new teachers.





 














</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-28_ pf-text-1"><strong>Misconduct cases</strong> - In the 2022/23 academic year, the TRA handled around 900 teacher misconduct cases, underscoring its critical role in maintaining professional standards.






 














</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-30_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-31_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-32_ pf-heading-1-h3">Key definitions
</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-bQtKYq czWvgn pf-34_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-35_ pf-text-1"><strong>Qualified Teacher Status (QTS)</strong> - A professional qualification for teachers in England, confirming they have met the required standards to teach.

</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-37_ pf-text-1"><strong>Prohibition order</strong> - A sanction imposed by the TRA, preventing an individual from teaching indefinitely due to serious misconduct.





</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-39_ pf-text-1"><strong>Professional Conduct Panel (PCP)</strong> - A panel that reviews teacher misconduct cases and makes recommendations on sanctions.






</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-41_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-42_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-43_ pf-heading-1-h3">Recruitment and qualification
</h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-45_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">The TRA is responsible for awarding QTS, ensuring that only individuals who meet stringent criteria can teach in maintained schools in England. The process involves:
























</p><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-bQtKYq czWvgn pf-47_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-48_ pf-text-1"><strong>Assessment of credentials</strong> - Evaluating academic and professional qualifications.</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-50_ pf-text-1"><strong>Skills test</strong> - Assessing proficiency in numeracy and literacy.</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-52_ pf-text-1"><strong>Induction</strong> - Overseeing the statutory induction period for newly qualified teachers.







</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-54_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-55_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-56_ pf-heading-1-h3">Teacher misconduct
</h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-58_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">The TRA investigates allegations of serious teacher misconduct. This process includes:

























</p><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-bQtKYq czWvgn pf-60_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-61_ pf-text-1"><strong>Initial assessment </strong>- Determining if the allegations warrant a full investigation.</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-63_ pf-text-1"><strong>Investigation </strong>- Gathering evidence and interviewing witnesses.</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-65_ pf-text-1"><strong>Professional conduct panels </strong>- Conduct hearings to review the evidence and decide on sanctions.








</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-67_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-68_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-69_ pf-heading-1-h3">Ongoing professional standards
</h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-71_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">The TRA sets out and enforces the Teachers’ Standards, which outline the expectations for teachers' conduct and practice. These standards cover:


























</p><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-bQtKYq czWvgn pf-73_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-74_ pf-text-1"><strong>Professional attributes </strong>- Including relationships with pupils and adherence to policies.</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-76_ pf-text-1"><strong>Professional knowledge</strong> - Covering subject knowledge and curriculum requirements.</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-78_ pf-text-1"><strong>Professional skills</strong> - Encompassing planning, teaching, and assessment.
</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-80_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-81_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-82_ pf-heading-1-h3">Best practices for implementation of relevant legislation and regulations
</h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-84_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong> Compliance with the teachers’ standards</strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-86_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Schools and educational institutions must ensure that all teaching staff comply with the Teachers’ Standards. This involves regular performance reviews and professional development opportunities to address any areas of improvement.





















</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-88_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Robust recruitment processes</strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-90_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Institutions should implement thorough recruitment processes to verify the qualifications and backgrounds of potential teachers. This includes:























</p><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-bQtKYq czWvgn pf-92_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-93_ pf-text-1"><strong>Verification of QTS </strong>- Ensuring candidates have been awarded QTS by the TRA.</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-95_ pf-text-1"><strong>Background checks </strong>- Conducting DBS checks and reference verifications.
</li></ul><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-97_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Addressing misconduct promptly</strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-99_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Schools must have clear policies for addressing allegations of teacher misconduct. This includes:


























</p><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-bQtKYq czWvgn pf-101_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-102_ pf-text-1"><strong>Immediate reporting</strong> - Promptly reporting severe allegations to the TRA.&nbsp;</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-104_ pf-text-1"><strong>Internal investigations</strong> - Conducting initial investigations while maintaining confidentiality.</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-106_ pf-text-1"><strong>Support systems</strong> - Support the accused and the accuser during investigations.
</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-108_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-109_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-110_ pf-heading-1-h3">Recommendations
</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-bQtKYq czWvgn pf-112_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-113_ pf-text-1"><strong>Continuous Professional Development </strong>- Encourage teachers to engage in ongoing professional development to stay updated with the latest educational practices and standards.

</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-115_ pf-text-1"><strong>Clear policies and procedures</strong> - Develop and maintain clear policies for handling misconduct and ensure all staff know these procedures.








</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-117_ pf-text-1"><strong>Use of compliance management software</strong> - Leverage tools like ComplyPlus™ to effectively manage compliance with legislative and regulatory requirements.









</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-119_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-120_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-121_ pf-heading-1-h3">Conclusion
</h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-123_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(74, 144, 226);"></span>The Teaching Regulation Agency is indispensable in maintaining the integrity and quality of the teaching profession in England. By overseeing teacher qualifications, addressing misconduct, and enforcing professional standards, the TRA ensures that students receive a high-quality education from competent and ethical educators. Educational institutions must adhere to best practices to support the TRA’s mission and foster an environment of excellence and accountability.

